#Create a function with the arguments width and height
def rectangle_area(width, height):
#Define a variable with the multiplication of oth arguments
    area = float(width*height)
#Return the area of the rectangule
    return area

#Use your created function to calculate the area of a rectangle with width 3 and height 4. Another of width 5 and height 10, and another of width 8 and height 2. Show your results in the same cell with a description of each result

print(f"The area of the rectangle with width 3 and height 4 is {rectangle_area(3, 4)}")

print(f"The area of the rectangle with width 5 and height 10 is {rectangle_area(5, 10)}")

print(f"The area of the rectangle with width 8 and height 2 is {rectangle_area(8, 2)}")

The area of the rectangle with width 3 and height 4 is 12.0
The area of the rectangle with width 5 and height 10 is 50.0
The area of the rectangle with width 8 and height 2 is 16.0

EXERCISE 5

In [10]:
def f(x):
    return x**2
def central_difference(f, x, h):
    return (f(x+h)-f(x))/h
print(f"The derivative of f(x) = x^2 at x = 2 using h = 0.1 is {central_difference(f, 2, 0.1)}")
print(f"The derivative of f(x) = x^2 at x = 2 using h = 0.01 is {central_difference(f, 2, 0.01)}")
print(f"The derivative of f(x) = x^2 at x = 2 using h = 0.001 is {central_difference(f, 2, 0.001)}")

The derivative of f(x) = x^2 at x = 2 using h = 0.1 is 4.100000000000001
The derivative of f(x) = x^2 at x = 2 using h = 0.01 is 4.009999999999891
The derivative of f(x) = x^2 at x = 2 using h = 0.001 is 4.000999999999699
